  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and guidelines aimed at preventing money laundering. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is the primary international organization that sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Many countries have adopted FATF recommendations into their national laws, which typically include:\n\n1. Requirements for financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Keep detailed financial records\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\n2. International cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering activities\n\n3. Legal frameworks that criminalize money laundering as a specific offense\n\n4. Mechanisms for tracking and freezing suspicious financial transactions\n\n5. Regulations requiring banks and financial institutions to conduct due diligence on customers\n\nWhile specific implementation varies by country, most developed nations have robust anti-money laundering laws and cooperate internationally to detect and prevent such financial crimes.",
